<font color="#FF0000">TO JOE</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 13  7:05:46 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Joe,<br><br>
Thanks for your perspective. Even one voice of support and understanding is important. You clearly have an insight borne of personal experience.<br><br>
A problem is that there continues to be all too few who take interest in the 'NamVet situation. I see great interest and support in the psychological and psychiatric professions, an acknowledgement of the fallout of the war in its continuing saga in many minds. I see an occaisional politician trying to make a few brownie points. I see PBS addressing the subject more intensely and sensitively than most media. I see The Wall. I see my Brother vets. I see us here. Am I missing something? If I am, tell me. The rest of it seems nothing more than a sand trap.<br><br>
I hear people say that there must be healing and a move forward. How do you heal something when the cure is long since departed. This is 1997, not 1970. How do you turn back the clock to capture something you needed back then, in the context of back then, in the frame of mind back then, when you and the world have now irrevocably changed into something else.<br><br>
The Vietnam War does continue, and will continue long after most of us are history. I'm not sure what is the solution, now. I look toward the medical profession, a few close friends, family, and my Brothers of Choice. They remain my only opitions. Perhaps I am lucky I have what I have.<br><br>
Perhaps another good cry at The Wall will help a little more. <br><br>
Art <br><br>

